-- Japan, China, Indonesia, Philippines, Taiwan: Asia Bonds, Currency Preview
-- B y   F r a n c e s   Y o o n
-- 2010-10-04T22:29:46Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-04/japan-china-indonesia-philippines-taiwan-asia-bonds-currency-preview.html
The following events and economic
reports may influence trading in Asia’s local bonds and
currencies today. Yields and exchange rates are from the
previous trading session unless stated otherwise.  Japan: Chief Cabinet Secretary  Yoshito Sengoku  and Finance
Minister  Yoshihiko Noda  will hold media briefings after a
Cabinet meeting in the morning. Sengoku will have another press
briefing at 4 p.m. in Tokyo.  The Bank of Japan will conclude its two-day policy board
meeting in Tokyo, after which the central bank will release a
statement. Bank of Japan Governor  Masaaki Shirakawa  will hold a
media briefing at 3:30 p.m. in Tokyo.  The yield on the 1 percent government bond due September
2020 was at 0.935 percent, according to Japan Bond Trading Co.,
the nation’s largest interdealer debt broker.  The yen traded at 83.47 per dollar at 7:24 a.m. in Tokyo.  China: HSBC Holdings Plc and Markit Economics will release
the September reading for their services industry purchasing
managers’ index today. The index was at 57.6 for August.  The yield on the 2.53 percent note due in June 2015 was
2.65 percent on Sept. 30, the last day of trading before public
holidays in China. The yuan was at 6.6912 on Sept. 30.  Indonesia: Bank Indonesia will today keep its reference
rate unchanged at 6.5 percent for a 14th straight month,
according to 15 of 16 economists surveyed by Bloomberg.  The yield on the 11 percent bond due November 2020 was at
7.46 percent, according to the Inter Dealer Market Association.
The rupiah was at 8,946.  Philippines: The National Statistics Office in Manila will
report consumer prices for September at 9 a.m. local time. Year-
on-year inflation will stay at 4 percent, unchanged from the
previous month, according to a Bloomberg News survey.  The yield on the 6.125 percent debt due September 2020 was
6.20 percent, according to Philippine Dealing & Exchange Corp.
The peso was at 43.785 per dollar.  Taiwan: Consumer prices probably increased by 0.4 percent
in September from a year earlier, after falling in August for
the first time in eight months, a Bloomberg survey showed ahead
of the data to be released today.  The Taipei-based Central Bank of China (Taiwan) will report
foreign-exchange reserve holdings for September. Reserves rose
to $372.1 billion in August, from $370.1 billion in July.  The yield on the 1.125 percent note due September 2020 was
1.17 percent. The Taiwan dollar was at NT$31.250 per dollar.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Frances Yoon in Seoul at   fyoon2@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Sandy Hendry at   shendry@bloomberg.net  